th the Japanese and the Wang Jingwei regime in Nanjing. Characteristics of business in the decades prior to the war, including a preference for family firms and reluctance to become public corporations, distrust of government, opaqueness of business practices, and reliance of personal connections (guanxi) were critical to the survival of enterprises during the war and were reinforced by the war experience. Through consideration of the broader implications of the many responses to this complex era, Chinese Capitalists in Japan’s New Order makes a substantial contribution to larger discussions of the dynamics of World War II and of Chinese business culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSino-Japanese War, 1937-1945xEconomic aspectszChinazShanghai. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  abattle of shanghai.  abeijing.  abusiness culture.  abusiness.  acapitalism.  acentral china.  achangzhou.  achina.  achinese businessmen.  achinese corporations.  achinese history.  acollaboration.  acolonialism.  aconfucian capitalism.  acorporate culture.  acorporation.  aempire.  aentrepreneur.  afamily business.  agovernment regulation.  aguanxi.  ahistorical memory.  ainvasion.  ajapan.  ajapanese imperialism.  amilitary.  ananjing.  anationalist army.  anonfiction.  aoccupation.  arebellion.  aregime.  aresistance.  awang jingwei.  awar.  aworld war two.  aww2.  ayangzi.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023268640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092829940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928299423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520928299/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package